{"questionId":"7669","questionHtml":"<p>explain why the time coordinate of E in frame S is&nbsp;<span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"t = \\frac{L}{c}\">\n  <mi>t</mi>\n  <mo>=</mo>\n  <mfrac>\n    <mi>L</mi>\n    <mi>c</mi>\n  </mfrac>\n</math></span>.</p>","markschemeHtml":"<p><em><strong>ALTERNATIVE 1:</strong></em></p>\n<p>the time in frame S′ is <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"t' = \\frac{L}{c}\">\n  <msup>\n    <mi>t</mi>\n    <mo>′</mo>\n  </msup>\n  <mo>=</mo>\n  <mfrac>\n    <mi>L</mi>\n    <mi>c</mi>\n  </mfrac>\n</math></span> ✔</p>\n<p>but time is absolute in Galilean relativity so is the same in S ✔</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><em><strong>ALTERNATIVE 2:</strong></em></p>\n<p>In frame S, light rays travel at <em>c</em> + <em>v</em> ✔</p>\n<p><strong>so</strong> <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"t = \\frac{L}{{\\left( {c + v} \\right) - v}} = \\frac{L}{c}\">\n  <mi>t</mi>\n  <mo>=</mo>\n  <mfrac>\n    <mi>L</mi>\n    <mrow>\n      <mrow>\n        <mo>(</mo>\n        <mrow>\n          <mi>c</mi>\n          <mo>+</mo>\n          <mi>v</mi>\n        </mrow>\n        <mo>)</mo>\n      </mrow>\n      <mo>−</mo>\n      <mi>v</mi>\n    </mrow>\n  </mfrac>\n  <mo>=</mo>\n  <mfrac>\n    <mi>L</mi>\n    <mi>c</mi>\n  </mfrac>\n</math></span> ✔</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><em>In Alternative 1, they must refer to S'</em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"7669","referenceCode":"18N.3.SL.TZ0.3b.i","subjectId":"46-dp-physics-last-assessment-2024","title":"explain why the time coordinate of E in frame S is t = L c .","paper":"3","level":"SL","questionNumber":"b.i","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 2]","breadcrumbLabels":["Option A: Relativity","Option A: Relativity","Option A: Relativity (Core topics)","A.1 – The beginnings of relativity","Option A: Relativity","Option A: Relativity (Core topics)"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}}}